.TH NLEASH 1 "May 2026" "nleash" "User Commands"
.SH NAME
nleash \- limit outbound bandwidth for a process using cgroup v2 and eBPF
.SH SYNOPSIS
.B nleash
--pid PID --rate RATE [--burst SIZE]

.B nleash
--rate RATE [--burst SIZE] -- command [args...]

.B nleash
--pid PID --clear

.B nleash
--list [--json]

.B nleash
--stats [--pid PID] [--json]
.SH DESCRIPTION
nleash applies egress bandwidth limits to a process using cgroup v2 and a
small eBPF program attached at BPF_CGROUP_INET_EGRESS. It creates a child
cgroup under the target's existing cgroup, moves the process in, and attaches
a token-bucket rate limiter. Packets exceeding the rate are dropped; TCP
backs off via congestion control.

Ingress shaping is intentionally out of scope.
.PP
For non-root usage, nleash can exec a setuid-root helper (nleash-helper)
that performs the privileged operations. The helper enforces that non-root
callers can only act on their own processes and drops privileges before
executing commands.
.SH OPTIONS
.TP
.BR --pid " " PID
Target an existing process ID. Only sockets opened after the leash is
applied will be throttled (kernel limitation: socket-cgroup tags are set
at socket() time and not updated on task migration).
.TP
.BR --rate " " RATE
Egress rate. Accepts tc-style bit-per-second suffixes:
.BR bit ,
.BR kbit ,
.BR mbit ,
.BR gbit
(e.g.\&
.BR 500kbit ,
.BR 10mbit ).
.TP
.BR --burst " " SIZE
Token-bucket capacity in bytes. Accepts
.BR b ,
.BR kb ,
.BR mb
suffixes. Default is rate * 50ms with a 3KB floor.
.TP
.B --clear
Clear the leash for the given PID. Performs identity safety checks; if the
identity tuple (pid, starttime_ticks, boot_id) does not match the recorded
leash, nleash will only remove its own bpf/cgroup state and not touch any
live process.
.TP
.B --list
List current leashes (from /run/nleash/state.txt).
.TP
.B --stats
Show byte counters (passed, dropped) per leash from the BPF map.
.TP
.B --json
Machine-readable JSON for --list / --stats.
.SH REQUIREMENTS
- Linux with cgroup v2 mounted at /sys/fs/cgroup
- Kernel >= 5.15
- bpffs mounted at /sys/fs/bpf (systemd default)
- CAP_NET_ADMIN + CAP_BPF (or run via setuid helper)
.SH SAFETY
Leashes are keyed by (pid, starttime_ticks, boot_id). If the identity does
not match during --clear, nleash does not touch any live process and only
removes stale bpf/cgroup state.
.SH FILES
/run/nleash/state.txt
/run/nleash/nextid
/sys/fs/bpf/nleash/{prog,buckets,links/}
.SH SEE ALSO
.BR bpf (2),
.BR cgroups (7)
